# Curate From Channel

Add a new Frogo channel built around a known YouTube creator, series, or genre (e.g. "make an analog horror channel starting with The Boiled One"). Different from `curate-playlist`, which is purely topic-based — this one centers a specific creator/series and pulls their actual catalog plus genre-adjacent picks.

Use when the user names a creator, channel, series, or scene and asks to add it (e.g. "add a channel for X", "make a Y channel starting with Z", "build a playlist around <creator>").

## Two phases — keep them separate

This skill has **two distinct phases** that look similar but use different tools and serve different purposes. Mixing them up is what wastes time.

| Phase | Tool | Purpose | What you're looking for |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Discovery** | WebSearch + WebFetch | Editorial taste | Which videos are *canonical*, *viral*, *the entry point*. Adjacent creators in the same scene. Cultural context for descriptions. |
| **Extraction** | `curl` + `grep` | Raw data | Video IDs, titles, durations. |

**The mistake**: searching wikis/fan pages for video IDs. They never have them. Use them only for editorial guidance.
**The fix**: get the editorial verdict from wikis, then go to YouTube directly for the data.

## Steps

### 1. Discovery (research, parallel)

Fire 2-3 searches in parallel to learn the scene:

```
WebSearch: "best <genre> youtube series 2025"           → adjacent creators worth padding with
WebSearch: "<creator> most popular videos"              → which video is the anchor
WebSearch: "<series> explained"                          → cultural context for descriptions
```

Then optionally WebFetch one or two of the better-looking results (Collider lists, Tubefilter articles, Wikipedia) for editorial summaries. **Stop chasing wikis after the second 403** — they block bots aggressively.

What you should walk away with:
- The creator's `@handle` (or channel ID)
- Which 1-2 videos are the canonical anchor (usually the viral one)
- 1-2 genre-adjacent creators to pad with if the main channel is thin
- A few sentences of context to write good descriptions

What you should *not* try to extract from research: video IDs, durations, full episode lists. Those come from YouTube directly.

### 2. Extraction — scrape video IDs from each channel

```bash
curl -sL "https://www.youtube.com/@<handle>" | grep -oE '"videoId":"[^"]*"' | sort -u
```

The channel page HTML embeds 12-30 most recent video IDs inline. For shorts, also try `/@<handle>/shorts`. For full back catalog, use the RSS feed if you know the channel ID:

```bash
curl -sL "https://www.youtube.com/feeds/videos.xml?channel_id=<UC...>"
```

### 3. Extraction — titles + durations in parallel

Two reliable sources, both keyless:

**Title via noembed:**
```bash
curl -s "https://noembed.com/embed?url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=<id>" \
  | python3 -c "import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin).get('title','UNAVAILABLE'))"
```

**Duration via watch page HTML:**
```bash
curl -s "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=<id>" \
  | grep -oE '"lengthSeconds":"[0-9]+"' | head -1 | grep -oE '[0-9]+'
```

Parallelize with `xargs -P 8` — 30 videos in ~4s instead of ~30s sequential:

```bash
echo "id1 id2 id3 ..." | tr ' ' '\n' | xargs -I{} -P 8 sh -c '
  TITLE=$(curl -s "https://noembed.com/embed?url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v={}" \
    | python3 -c "import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin).get(\"title\",\"\"))")
  DUR=$(curl -s "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v={}" \
    | grep -oE "\"lengthSeconds\":\"[0-9]+\"" | head -1 | grep -oE "[0-9]+")
  echo "{}|$DUR|$TITLE"
'
```

A noembed 200 also confirms availability — no separate check needed.

### 4. Curate (use the discovery phase here!)

This is where the Phase-1 research pays off. Filter the raw scrape:

- **Lead with the canonical anchor.** The discovery phase told you which video is the entry point — that's position 1. Don't just sort by upload date.
- Drop sub-30s art shorts and channel trailers
- Drop ads / merch promos (e.g. "PLUSH ADVERT")
- If the main channel is thin (<6 long-form videos), pull 4-6 more from the genre-adjacent creators discovery surfaced. Scrape *their* channels the same way.
- Write descriptions using the cultural context from research, not just titles. ("Doctor Nowhere's viral analog horror — a hijacked broadcast reveals PHEN-228" is better than "A short horror video.")

