### 6. Verify

```bash
curl -s "https://tv.aimhuge.com/watch/<slug>" -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}"
```

200 = live. Report URL to the user.

## Anti-patterns

- ❌ Searching wikis for *video IDs* — they don't embed them. Search wikis for *editorial guidance* instead.
- ❌ Chasing fandom/tvtropes/knowyourmeme past two 403 responses — they block bots; pivot to a different source.
- ❌ Sequential `for vid in ...; do curl ...` — always parallelize with `xargs -P`.
- ❌ Parsing `youtube.com/@handle` via WebFetch — returns minified JS, not rendered HTML. Use `curl | grep` directly.
- ❌ Skipping discovery entirely and just dumping the channel's most recent uploads in upload order — you'll miss the canonical anchor and lose cultural context for descriptions.

## Speed budget

Target: ~8-12 tool calls total.
- Discovery: 2-3 WebSearches in parallel + 0-2 WebFetches = 3-5 calls
- Extraction: 1 channel scrape + 1 parallel metadata fan-out = 2 calls
- Insert + verify: 2 calls

If you're at 15+ calls and still researching, you're chasing wikis. Stop and pivot to direct scraping.

## Speed tip: Haiku subagent for repeat runs

The extraction + insert phases are pure mechanism. For batch jobs (e.g. "add 3 channels"), spawn this as a `general-purpose` subagent with `model: haiku` per channel and run them in parallel.
